2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Kate Kane <br /><small>Batwoman</small>\n |Ruby Rose {{note label|main|M|}} \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Clark Kent <br /><small>Superman</small>\n |Tyler Hoechlin<ref name=CrisisInfinite>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/11/21/crisis-on-infinite-earths-spoilers-flash-supergirl-batwoman-episodes/|title='Crisis on Infinite Earths' Crossover Spoilers: The Search for 'Smallville,' Sara vs. Mia, Black Lightning and More|work=TV Line|first=Matt Webb|last=Mitovich|date=November 21, 2019|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Sara Lance <br /><small>White Canary</small>\n|Caity Lotz<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Lois Lane\n|Elizabeth Tulloch<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Lex Luthor\n|Jon Cryer<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Lyla Michaels <br /><small> Harbringer</small>\n|Audrey Marie Anderson\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mar Novu <br /><small>The Monitor</small>\n|LaMonica Garrett<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ray Palmer<br /><small>The Atom</small>\n| Brandon Routh\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mick Rory <br /><small>Heat Wave</small>\n|Dominic Purcell<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mia Smoak <br /><small>Green Arrow</small>\n|Katherine McNamara<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Iris West\n|Candice Patton<ref name=CrisisInfinite/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:#ddf;\" scope=\"row\" |\n\n===Introduced outside the Arrowverse===\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | John Constantine\n| Matt Ryan\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Clark Kent <br/><small>Superman{{note label|Earth-96|96}}</small>\n| Brandon Routh<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20191121cw03/ |title=(#108) \"Crisis on Infinite Earths: Part Two\" |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20191122035054/http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20191121cw03/ |archive-date=November 22, 2019 |access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Arrowverse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arrowverse actors, List of}}\n[[Category:Lists of DC Comics television characters]]\n[[Category:Lists of actors by American television series]]\n[[Category:Lists of actors by crime television series]]\n[[Category:Lists of actors by drama television series]]\n[[Category:Lists of actors by science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Arrowverse|Cast members]]\n", "name_user": "Ditto51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Flash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Arrowverse_cast_members"}
{"title_page": "Sit River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Sit \n| name_native       = \u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c\n| image             = \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430. \u0434. \u041b\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e.jpg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| image_caption     = The memorial on the Sit' battlefield\n| map               = Rybinsk vdhr eng.svg\n| map_caption       = Map of the [[Rybinsk Reservoir]] basin. The Sit is shown on the map.\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n| length            = {{convert|113|km|abbr=on}}\n| source1_location  = \n| source1_elevation = \n| source1_coordinates = \n| mouth             = [[Rybinsk Reservoir]]\n| mouth_location    = \n| mouth_coordinates = {{Coord|58|18|41|N|37|52|53|E|display=it|region:RU-ARK_type:river_source:dewiki}}\n| discharge1_avg    = \n| progression       = [[Rybinsk Reservoir]]\u2192 {{RVolga}}\n| basin_size        = {{convert|2370|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left  = \n| tributaries_right = \n}}\nThe '''Sit''' (\u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c) is a tributary of the [[Rybinsk Reservoir]] (nominally, of the [[Mologa River]])..<ref name=\"bse\">[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article102677.html Great Soviet Encyclopaedia]</ref> The river flows for {{convert|159|km|mi}} through [[Sonkovsky District]] of [[Tver Oblast]] and [[Nekouzsky District|Nekouzsky]] and [[Breytovsky District]]s of [[Yaroslavl Oblast]]s of [[Russia]] before entering the Rybinsk Reservoir near the large village of [[Breitovo]]. Its average width varies from {{convert|40|to|50|m|ft}} The river mouth is about {{convert|1500|m|ft}} wide. The [[drainage basin]] occupies some {{convert|1900|km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"bse\"/> The river is {{convert|159|km|mi}} long.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=175657|script-title=ru:\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c|publisher=State Water Register of Russia|language=Russian|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe river gives its name to the bloody [[Battle of the Sit River]] (1238). In the [[Middle Age]]s the valley of the Sit River belonged to a branch of the princely [[Yaroslavl Principality|House of Yaroslavl]]. The princes of the Sit', or [[Sitsky]], joined the service of the Grand Dukes of [[Muscovy]] in the 15th century. The family survived into the 17th century and was closely related by blood to the [[Romanovs]].<ref>[http://www.biografija.ru/show_bio.aspx?id=118380 Russian Biographical Dictionary]</ref>\n\nThe source of the Sit is in the north of Sonkovsky District, close to the village of [[Saburovo, Sonkovsky District, Tver Oblast|Saburovo]]. The river flows northeast, enters Yaroslavl Oblast, and turns south. By the [[Village#Russia|selo]] of [[Voznesenskoye, Nekouzsky District, Yaroslavl Oblast|Voznesenskoye]] it turns east and eventually north. The mouth of the Sit is in the selo of [[Breytovo]]. Before the Rybinsk Reservoir was filled, the Sit was a tributary of the Mologa River.\n\nThe drainage basin of the sit includes the eastern part of [[Krasnokholmsky District]] of Tver Oblast, the eastern part of Sonkovsky District, the western part of Nekouzsky District, and some areas in Breytovsky District. The district centers [[Sonkovo]] and Breytovo lie in the drainage basin of the Sit.\n\nIn the early 20th century the valley of the Sit River was home to the ''[[Sitskari]]'' ([[:ru:\u0441\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0438|ru]]), an ethnic group of short fair-haired people speaking a [[Northern Russian dialects|Northern dialect]] of the [[Russian language]]. It is thought that they had a mixture of [[Lithuania]]n or some other [[Balts|Baltic]] ancestry.<ref>[http://www.booksite.ru/fulltext/rus/sian/6.htm \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u044d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u0410\u041d: \u042d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u044b \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Volga River}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Yaroslavl Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tver Oblast]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Sit \n| name_native       = \u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c\n| image             = \u0421\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430. \u0434. \u041b\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e.jpg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| image_caption     = The memorial on the Sit' battlefield\n| map               = Rybinsk vdhr eng.svg\n| map_caption       = Map of the [[Rybinsk Reservoir]] basin. The Sit is shown on the map.\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n| length            = {{convert|113|km|abbr=on}}\n| source1_location  = \n| source1_elevation = \n| source1_coordinates = \n| mouth             = [[Mologa River|Mologa]]\n| mouth_location    = [[Rybinsk Reservoir]]\n| mouth_coordinates = {{Coord|58|18|41|N|37|52|53|E|display=it|region:RU-ARK_type:river_source:dewiki}}\n| discharge1_avg    = \n| progression       = {{RMologa}}\n| basin_size        = {{convert|2370|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left  = \n| tributaries_right = \n}}\nThe '''Sit''' (\u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c) is a tributary of the [[Rybinsk Reservoir]] (nominally, of the [[Mologa River]])..<ref name=\"bse\">[http://bse.sci-lib.com/article102677.html Great Soviet Encyclopaedia]</ref> The river flows for {{convert|159|km|mi}} through [[Sonkovsky District]] of [[Tver Oblast]] and [[Nekouzsky District|Nekouzsky]] and [[Breytovsky District]]s of [[Yaroslavl Oblast]]s of [[Russia]] before entering the Rybinsk Reservoir near the large village of [[Breitovo]]. Its average width varies from {{convert|40|to|50|m|ft}} The river mouth is about {{convert|1500|m|ft}} wide. The [[drainage basin]] occupies some {{convert|1900|km2|mi2}}.<ref name=\"bse\"/> The river is {{convert|159|km|mi}} long.<ref name=\"register\">{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=175657|script-title=ru:\u0420\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0421\u0438\u0442\u044c|publisher=State Water Register of Russia|language=Russian|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe river gives its name to the bloody [[Battle of the Sit River]] (1238). In the [[Middle Age]]s the valley of the Sit River belonged to a branch of the princely [[Yaroslavl Principality|House of Yaroslavl]]. The princes of the Sit', or [[Sitsky]], joined the service of the Grand Dukes of [[Muscovy]] in the 15th century. The family survived into the 17th century and was closely related by blood to the [[Romanovs]].<ref>[http://www.biografija.ru/show_bio.aspx?id=118380 Russian Biographical Dictionary]</ref>\n\nThe source of the Sit is in the north of Sonkovsky District, close to the village of [[Saburovo, Sonkovsky District, Tver Oblast|Saburovo]]. The river flows northeast, enters Yaroslavl Oblast, and turns south. By the [[Village#Russia|selo]] of [[Voznesenskoye, Nekouzsky District, Yaroslavl Oblast|Voznesenskoye]] it turns east and eventually north. The mouth of the Sit is in the selo of [[Breytovo]]. Before the Rybinsk Reservoir was filled, the Sit was a tributary of the Mologa River.\n\nThe drainage basin of the sit includes the eastern part of [[Krasnokholmsky District]] of Tver Oblast, the eastern part of Sonkovsky District, the western part of Nekouzsky District, and some areas in Breytovsky District. The district centers [[Sonkovo]] and Breytovo lie in the drainage basin of the Sit.\n\nIn the early 20th century the valley of the Sit River was home to the ''[[Sitskari]]'' ([[:ru:\u0441\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0438|ru]]), an ethnic group of short fair-haired people speaking a [[Northern Russian dialects|Northern dialect]] of the [[Russian language]]. It is thought that they had a mixture of [[Lithuania]]n or some other [[Balts|Baltic]] ancestry.<ref>[http://www.booksite.ru/fulltext/rus/sian/6.htm \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u044d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u0410\u041d: \u042d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u044b \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Volga River}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Yaroslavl Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tver Oblast]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sit_River"}
{"title_page": "Concussion (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 American sports drama film directed by Peter Landesman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Concussion\n| image          = Concussion poster.jpg\n| alt            = Bennet Omalu in front of some football helmets\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Landesman]]\n| producer       = {{plain list|\n* [[Ridley Scott]]\n* [[Giannina Facio]]\n* David Wolthoff\n* Larry Shuman\n* Elizabeth Cantillon\n}}\n| writer         = Peter Landesman\n| based on       = {{Based on |Game Brain|[[Jeanne Marie Laskas]]}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Smith]]\n* [[Alec Baldwin]]\n* [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]]\n* [[Arliss Howard]]\n* [[Paul Reiser]]\n* [[Luke Wilson]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]]}}\n* [[David Morse (actor)|David Morse]]\n* [[Albert Brooks]]\n}}\n| music          = [[James Newton Howard]]\n| cinematography = [[Salvatore Totino]]\n| editing        = [[William Goldenberg]]\n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=deadline-premiere/>\n* [[LStar Capital]]<ref name=deadline-premiere>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/concussion-world-premiere-afi-fest-2015-1201560842/|title='Concussion' To Get World Premiere At AFI Fest|last=Busch|first=Anita|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=February 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927075019/http://deadline.com/2015/09/concussion-world-premiere-afi-fest-2015-1201560842/|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Village Roadshow Pictures]]<ref name=deadline-premiere/>\n* [[Scott Free Productions]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/11/concussion-review-will-smith-scores-touchdown-with-grim-nfl-expose/#57e3598266ce|title='Concussion' Review: Will Smith Scores Touchdown With Timely NFL Muckraker|website=forbes.com|publisher=[[Forbes]]|author=Scott Mendelson|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129043817/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/11/concussion-review-will-smith-scores-touchdown-with-grim-nfl-expose/#57e3598266ce|archive-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|10|[[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]]|2015|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:39--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/concussion-film-0 | title=''CONCUSSION'' (12A) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 2, 2015 | accessdate=November 2, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101144510/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/concussion-film-0 | archive-date=January 1, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $35\u201357 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2015_film_study_v3_WEB.pdf|title=2015 Feature Film Study|last=McDonald|first=Adrian|date=June 15, 2016|publisher=Film L.A.|access-date=June 16, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810062318/https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2015_film_study_v3_WEB.pdf |archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=BOM/>\n| gross = $48.6 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=concussion2015.htm |title=Concussion |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824213033/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=concussion2015.htm |archive-date=August 24, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Concussion''''' is a 2015 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[Sports film|sports drama]] film directed and written by [[Peter Landesman]], based on the expos\u00e9 \"Game Brain\" by [[Jeanne Marie Laskas]], published in 2009 by ''[[GQ]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bennet Omalu, Concussions, and the NFL: How One Doctor Changed Football Forever|url=https://www.gq.com/story/nfl-players-brain-dementia-study-memory-concussions|work=[[GQ]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|last=Laskas|first=Jeanne Marie|date=September 14, 2009|accessdate=February 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151111053002/http://www.gq.com/story/nfl-players-brain-dementia-study-memory-concussions|archive-date=November 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Set in 2002, the film stars [[Will Smith]] as [[Bennet Omalu|Dr. Bennet Omalu]], a forensic pathologist who fights against the [[National Football League]] trying to suppress his research on [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE) brain degeneration suffered by professional football players. It also stars [[Alec Baldwin]]. \n\nThe film premiered at [[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]] on November 11, 2015 and was released  by [[Columbia Pictures]] on December 25, 2015. The film grossed $48 million worldwide and received mixed reviews, although Smith earned a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] nomination.\n\n==Plot==\n\n[[Steelers]] [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] [[Mike Webster]] is found dead in his [[pickup truck]], after years of [[Self-harm|self-mutilation]] and [[homelessness]]. Before his death, [[Justin Strzelczyk]], a former fellow [[American Football|football]] player, confides in Webster that he is starting to lose his memory, is saying odd things to his children, and nearly threw his wife against the wall. A disoriented Webster brushes Strzelczyk's worries off, and deliriously tells him that the most important thing \"is to finish the game,\" reciting what he said during his [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] speech.\n\n[[Bennet Omalu|Dr. Bennet Omalu]] (Will Smith), a [[Forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]] with the [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]] [[coroner]]'s office, handles Webster's [[autopsy]]. He wonders how an otherwise healthy man could have degenerated so quickly, and makes it a point to figure out why he died of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at only fifty years of age. Dr. Omalu closely examines [[Microscope slide|microscope slides]] of Webster's brain and sees evidence of severe [[brain damage|neurotrauma]], concluding that Webster died as a result of the long-term effects of repeated blows to the head, a disorder he terms [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE). With the help of former Steelers [[team doctor]] Dr. Julian Bailes, fellow [[Neurology|neurologist]] [[Steven T. DeKosky|Dr. Steven DeKosky]] and county coroner [[Cyril Wecht|Dr. Cyril Wecht]], Dr. Omalu publishes his findings in [[Neurosurgery_(journal)|''Neurosurgery'']], which are dismissed by the [[National Football League|NFL]].\n\nOver several years, Dr. Omalu discovers that three additional deceased NFL players, [[Justin Strzelczyk]] (2004), [[Terry Long (American football)|Terry Long]] (2005), and [[Andre Waters]] (2006), exhibited symptoms very similar to Webster's. He persuades newly appointed NFL commissioner [[Roger Goodell]] to allow him to present his findings before a player safety committee. However, the NFL does not take him seriously, and he is barred from the committee meeting, forcing the former NFL employee Bailes to give the presentation in place of Dr. Omalu. However, the meeting is a set up, where the NFL claims that the players' head trauma is unrelated to football, but rather, due to past injuries. As he leaves the meeting, former [[National Football League Players Association|NFL Players Association]] executive [[Dave Duerson]] angrily confronts Dr. Omalu and tells him to \"go back to [[Africa]].\"\n\nDr. Omalu is subjected to considerable pressure to back down from his efforts, as football is a widely beloved sport in [[Pittsburgh]], having provided jobs and allowed men to go to college. Wecht is subjected to a politically motivated prosecution on corruption charges, and Dr. Omalu is forced to leave Pittsburgh soon after, lest he be [[deportation|deported]], or sent to prison on petty charges as punishment for tarnishing the NFL's image. Before leaving, he urges the NFL to tell the truth. Dr. Omalu's wife, Prema, suffers a [[miscarriage]] after being followed in her car. The Omalus are forced to leave their dream home outside Pittsburgh, relocating to [[Lodi, California]] where he takes a job with the [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin County]] coroner's office.\n\nThree years later, Dr. Omalu is vindicated when Duerson commits [[suicide]] due to an increasing inability to cope with worsening [[cognitive skill|cognitive function]]. In his [[suicide note]], Duerson acknowledges that Dr. Omalu was right, and offers his brain for future research. Dr. Omalu is invited to address an NFLPA conference on concussions and CTE. He informs them that he once wished he had never known Mike Webster, but by knowing him, he has the responsibility to inform NFL players of the true risks that they take by playing. He says that he holds no resentment for the NFL and tells them to forgive themselves and be at peace. Amid growing scrutiny from [[United States Congress|Congress]], the NFL is forced to take the concussion issue more seriously, and in 2011, [[2011 NFL lockout|NFL players sue the league]] for not properly informing them of the risk of CTE. Dr. Omalu is offered the job of [[Medical examiner|Chief Medical Examiner]] for the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], but the closing credits show Omalu turning the offer down to remain with his family in Lodi, becoming [[Naturalization|naturalized]] as a [[Citizenship of the United States|U.S. citizen]] in February 2015. A final montage includes reports of [[Junior Seau]]'s suicide in 2012 and subsequent [[Concussions in American football#Federal NFL concussion litigation|lawsuits]] brought against the NFL by thousands of former players.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Will Smith]] as Dr. [[Bennet Omalu]]\n* [[Alec Baldwin]] as Dr. Julian Bailes\n* [[Albert Brooks]] as Dr. [[Cyril Wecht]]\n* [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]] as Prema Mutiso\n* [[David Morse]] as [[Mike Webster]]\n** [[Ben McDonnell]] as young [[Mike Webster]]\n* [[Arliss Howard]] as Dr. [[Joseph Maroon]]\n* [[Mike O'Malley]] as Daniel Sullivan\n* [[Eddie Marsan]] as Dr. [[Steven T. DeKosky]]\n* [[Hill Harper]] as Christopher Jones\n* [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]] as [[Dave Duerson]]\n* [[Stephen Moyer]] as Dr. Ron Hamilton\n* [[Richard T. Jones]] as [[Andre Waters]]\n* [[Paul Reiser]] as Dr. Elliot Pellman\n* [[Luke Wilson]] as [[Roger Goodell]]\n* [[Sara Lindsey]] as Gracie\n* [[Matt Willig|Matthew Willig]] as [[Justin Strzelczyk]]\n* [[Bitsie Tulloch]] as Keana Strzelczyk\n* [[Eme Ikwuakor]] as [[Amobi Okoye]]\n* [[Phillip Chorba]] as the technician\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[Ridley Scott]]'s idea of an NFL concussion film was inspired by Dr. Bennett Omalu's study about former NFL stars [[Junior Seau]] and [[Dave Duerson]], both of whom committed suicide after suffering from [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE). Scott was set to direct after his film ''[[Exodus: Gods and Kings]]'', while he and Facio were looking for an A-list writer.<ref name=Concussions>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Ridley Scott To Direct Film About Deadly Effects Of Concussions In Football Players|url=https://deadline.com/2013/11/ridley-scott-to-direct-film-about-deadly-effects-of-concussions-in-football-players-630082/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 7, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912132011/http://deadline.com/2013/11/ridley-scott-to-direct-film-about-deadly-effects-of-concussions-in-football-players-630082/|archive-date=September 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In November and December 2013, two more NFL concussion films were in development, first ''Game Time Decision'' with writer/director and former NFL training camp attendee [[wide receiver]] [[Matthew A. Cherry]] and actor [[Isaiah Washington]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Isaiah Washington, Matthew Cherry Huddle On Football Concussion Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2013/11/isaiah-washington-matthew-cherry-huddle-on-football-concussion-pic-634239/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 13, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211120557/http://deadline.com/2013/11/isaiah-washington-matthew-cherry-huddle-on-football-concussion-pic-634239/|archive-date=February 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and another film ''[[League of Denial]]'' with producers [[Walter Parkes]] and [[Laurie MacDonald]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=A Collision Of Football Concussion Projects: Parkes/MacDonald Options NFL Head Injury Expose 'League Of Denial' For Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2013/12/a-collision-of-football-concussion-projects-parkesmacdonald-options-nfl-head-injury-expose-league-of-denial-for-pic-648245/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007021549/http://deadline.com/2013/12/a-collision-of-football-concussion-projects-parkesmacdonald-options-nfl-head-injury-expose-league-of-denial-for-pic-648245/|archive-date=October 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Landesman had based his script on the 2009 [[GQ]] article ''Game Brain'' by [[Jeanne Marie Laskas]].<ref name=Landesman-Sony>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Will Smith Eyeing Gridiron Concussion Pic At Sony With Peter Landesman Directing|url=https://deadline.com/2014/06/will-smith-eyeing-gridiron-concussion-pic-739681/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=June 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926155201/http://deadline.com/2014/06/will-smith-eyeing-gridiron-concussion-pic-739681/|archive-date=September 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Smith and Marsan previously appeared together in the 2008 [[superhero film]] ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]''. It received $14.4 million in film tax credits from [[Pennsylvania]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] started on October 27, 2014, in [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], and filmed there through mid-January. One of the film's key scenes was shot in Altius Restaurant in the [[Mount Washington (Pittsburgh)|Mt. Washington]] section of Pittsburgh. Other area scenes were shot at a church in Pittsburgh's [[Hill District]], the [[Carnegie Free Library of Braddock|Braddock Carnegie Library]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The Will Smith crew filmed at Braddock Carnegie Library this week|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/12/04/The-Will-Smith-film-continued-production-at-Braddock-Carnegie-Library-this-week/stories/201412040306|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|author=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2018|publisher=PG Publishing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712084116/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/12/04/The-Will-Smith-film-continued-production-at-Braddock-Carnegie-Library-this-week/stories/201412040306|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and in [[downtown Pittsburgh]].<ref name=\"Vancheri\">{{cite web|first=Barbara|last=Vancheri|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/10/31/Will-Smith-movie-shooting-around-town/stories/201410310038|title=Will Smith football movie shooting in Pittsburgh|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=October 31, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2018|publisher=PG Publishing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712083943/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/10/31/Will-Smith-movie-shooting-around-town/stories/201410310038|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[James Newton Howard]] composed the score for the film. [[Klayton]] (frontman of [[Celldweller]]) provided synth programming for the score.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/celldweller/posts/10153595624591672|author=Klayton|publisher=[[Facebook]]|work=[[Celldweller]] official page |date=August 31, 2015|title=By now, most of you have heard that there's a new Will Smith movie called \"Concussion\" coming out. Some of you probably know that it's being scored by James Newton Howard.|accessdate=August 31, 2015|author-link=Klayton}}</ref> R&B singer [[Leon Bridges]] provided a new song, called \"So Long\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/leon-bridges-so-long-concussion-will-smith-nfl-1201620991/|title='Concussion': Leon Bridges Writes Song for Will Smith Drama|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 19, 2015|first=Kristopher|last=Tapley|accessdate=July 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712054549/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/leon-bridges-so-long-concussion-will-smith-nfl-1201620991/|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe first [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] was released on YouTube on August 31, 2015 by Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sony Pictures Entertainment|title=Concussion - Official Trailer (2015) - Will Smith|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Io6hPdC41RM|accessdate=August 31, 2015|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=August 31, 2015|author-link=Sony Pictures Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904021542/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Io6hPdC41RM|archive-date=September 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sony released the film on December 25, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Will Smith's 'Concussion' Drama Set for Christmas Release|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-smiths-concussion-drama-set-for-christmas-release-1201416809/|accessdate=January 28, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130024013/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-smiths-concussion-drama-set-for-christmas-release-1201416809/|archive-date=January 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Marketing included advertisements for the film airing during NFL games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chase|first1=Chris|title=The NFL-shaming 'Concussion' aired a commercial during Thanksgiving game|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/11/concussion-trailer-will-smith-thanksgiving-nfl-game-detroit-philadelphia-allowed-to-air-during-nfl-games|accessdate=December 2, 2015|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129081438/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/11/concussion-trailer-will-smith-thanksgiving-nfl-game-detroit-philadelphia-allowed-to-air-during-nfl-games|archive-date=November 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Concussion'' was released on [[Digital distribution|Digital HD]] on March 15, 2016, before being released two weeks later on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]] and 4K Ultra HD on March 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7690/concussion|title=Concussion (2015)|publisher=DVDs Release Dates|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129115055/http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7690/concussion|archive-date=January 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Concussion'' grossed $34.5 million in North America and $14.1 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $48.6 million, against a budget of $35 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film opened on December 25, 2015 alongside ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]'', ''[[Joy (film)|Joy]]'', ''[[Point Break (2015 film)|Point Break]]'' and the [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] of ''[[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]''. In its opening weekend, the film was projected to gross $8\u201310 million from 2,841 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-box-office-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201670872/|title='Force Awakens' Will Own Christmas Weekend As Five Wide Releases Join The Fray \u2013 Box Office Preview|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 21, 2015|accessdate=December 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223014719/http://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-box-office-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201670872/|archive-date=December 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It eventually grossed $10.5 million, finishing 7th at the box office.<ref name=CinemaScore/> Due to Smith's star status and the $35 million production budget, the film was considered a box office disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/concussion-adds-to-will-smiths-growing-list-of-recent-box-office-disappointments-whats-going-on-20160111|title='Concussion' adds to Will Smith's recent list of box office disappointments. What's going on?|first=Tambay|last=Obenson|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=January 11, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224082338/http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/concussion-adds-to-will-smiths-growing-list-of-recent-box-office-disappointments-whats-going-on-20160111|archive-date=February 24, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsworldnews.com/articles/55400/20151226/concussion-movie-update-low-box-office-numbers-proves-people-arent-really-concerned-about-cte-video.htm|title=Concussion Movie Update: Low box office numbers prove people aren't really concerned about CTE|first=Eduardo|last=Mendez|work=Sports World News|date=December 26, 2015|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070618/http://www.sportsworldnews.com/articles/55400/20151226/concussion-movie-update-low-box-office-numbers-proves-people-arent-really-concerned-about-cte-video.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 59% based on 199 reviews, with an average rating of 6.08/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Concussion'' lands a solid, well-acted hit on its impressively timely subject matter, even if its traditional, sports drama structure is a little too safe to deserve a full-on dance in the end zone.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/concussion_2015/ |title=Concussion (2015) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927121748/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/concussion_2015/ |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 55 out of 100, based on 39 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/concussion-2015 |title=Concussion Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116092724/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/concussion-2015 |archive-date=January 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[CinemaScore]], audiences gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-weekend-box-office-record-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201672899/ |title='Daddy', 'Joy' & 'Hateful Eight' Reap Fortune As 'Star Wars' Halo Effect Impacts B.O... Can 'Force Awakens' Hit $1 Billion In U.S.? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |first1=Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro |first2=Anita |last2=Busch |date=December 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613000029/https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-weekend-box-office-record-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201672899/ |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWill Smith's performance was praised for being \"sensitive [and] understated\" by ''[[The Denver Post]]''. [[Alec Baldwin]]'s performance was well-received, although his accent was criticized.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_29312021/concussion-movie-review-sensitive-will-smith-anchors-film |title=\"Concussion\" movie review: A sensitive Will Smith anchors film that hits home |date=December 25, 2015 |author=The Associated Press |website=[[The Denver Post]] |publisher=[[Digital First Media]] |accessdate=January 20, 2016 |author-link=The Associated Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127090227/http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_29312021/concussion-movie-review-sensitive-will-smith-anchors-film |archive-date=January 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"95%\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Awards\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[African-American Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Actor\n| [[Will Smith]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Black Reel Awards]]\n| Outstanding Actor, Motion Picture\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Motion Picture\n|''Concussion''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Supporting Actress, Motion Picture\n| [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Ensembles\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[73rd Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Drama]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[The Razzie Redeemer Award]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Film Awards]]\n| Actor of the Year\n| Will Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2016 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Male Performance\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| True Story\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[NAACP Image Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacpimageawards.net/main_winners_nominees.html|title=Nominees|work=47th NACCP Image Awards|publisher=[[NAACP Image Award]]s|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828102253/http://www.naacpimageawards.net/main_winners_nominees.html|archivedate=August 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Motion Picture|Outstanding Motion Picture]]\n|''Concussion''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture]]\n| Gugu Mbatha-Raw\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]]\n| Creative Impact in Acting Award\n| Will Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Directors to Watch\n| [[Peter Landesman]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[20th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| Best Actor\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\nFamily members of [[Dave Duerson]], a former NFL player who suffered from CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and committed suicide, claimed the film portrayed Duerson in a bad light. In one scene, Duerson's character called Omalu's character a \"quack\" in addition to telling him \"to go back to Africa\" and \"get away from our game.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = Dave Duerson's Family Says 'Concussion' Film Smears Him|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/sports/football/concussion-movie-smears-dave-duerson-his-family-says.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|publisher = The New York Times Company|date = December 16, 2015|access-date = December 17, 2015|first = Ken|last = Belson|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151217035951/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/sports/football/concussion-movie-smears-dave-duerson-his-family-says.html|archive-date = December 17, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In another scene, Duerson is shown mocking former NFL player [[Andre Waters]] when he filed an application for benefits in connection with head injuries he sustained while playing in the NFL. Duerson's family members called these scenes false. In response, Landesman, the film's director, stated that the film was \"emotionally and spiritually accurate all the way through\".<ref name=\":0\"/> When asked about the accuracy of the film, Steven DeKosky also noted that it took numerous liberties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/neurology/headtrauma/55657|title='The Great DeKosky' Talks CTE & Concussion|date=January 14, 2016|website=www.medpagetoday.com|access-date=February 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180046/https://www.medpagetoday.com/neurology/headtrauma/55657|archive-date=February 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n \n''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' science writer Daniel Engber, who has been skeptical of the link between CTE and the deaths of players found to have had it,<ref name=\"Engber Seau article\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2012/05/junior_seau_s_suicide_are_concussions_responsible_.html|last=Engber|first=Daniel|title=The Concussion Panic|newspaper=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|publisher=The Slate Group|date=May 9, 2012|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421101746/http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2012/05/junior_seau_s_suicide_are_concussions_responsible_.html|archive-date=April 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> called the film inaccurate in other ways, for example suggesting that Wecht's arrest on corruption charges was motivated by Omalu's paper, when in fact it was published three months afterwards. \"[The film] feeds into a pervasive myth at the center of the national discussion over football and head injuries,\" he charges.<ref name=\"Engber criticism\">{{cite web|last1=Engber|first1=Daniel|title=Concussion Lies|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2015/12/the_truth_about_will_smith_s_concussion_and_bennet_omalu.html|newspaper=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|publisher=The Slate Group|accessdate=December 26, 2015|date=December 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225174843/http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2015/12/the_truth_about_will_smith_s_concussion_and_bennet_omalu.html|archive-date=December 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In particular, he cites a 2012 [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] study<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Baron|first1=Sherry L.|last2=Hein|first2=Misty J.|last3=Lehman|first3=Everett|last4=Gersic|first4=Christine M.|title=Body Mass Index, Playing Position, Race, and the Cardiovascular Mortality of Retired Professional Football Players|journal=[[American Journal of Cardiology]]|date=March 15, 2012|volume=109|issue=6|pages=889\u2013896|url=http://www.ajconline.org/article/S0002-9149(11)03387-X/fulltext|accessdate=December 26, 2015|doi=10.1016/j.amjcard.2011.10.050|pmid=22284915|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311113236/http://www.ajconline.org/article/S0002-9149(11)03387-X/fulltext|archive-date=March 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> indicating that football players, on average compared to the population as a whole, live longer and generally healthier lives, though the study also indicates, as Engber concedes, that former football players are also more likely to suffer, and die, from neurodegenerative disease.<ref name=\"Engber criticism\" />\n\nMore recent research and thinking also looks at the steady accumulation of subconcussive blows, in addition to symptomatic concussions, as a major contribution factor in the development of CTE.<ref>[https://www.bu.edu/sph/2018/01/18/hits-not-concussions-cause-cte/ Hits, Not Concussions, Cause CTE] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726005558/https://www.bu.edu/sph/2018/01/18/hits-not-concussions-cause-cte/ |date=July 26, 2018 }}, Boston University School of Public, Jan. 18, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.menshealth.com/health/a21346159/should-kids-play-football/ We Know Football Is Dangerous. So Why Are We Still Letting Our Sons Play It?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725214648/https://www.menshealth.com/health/a21346159/should-kids-play-football/ |date=July 25, 2018 }}, ''Men's Health'', Andrew Lawrence, July 10, 2018.</ref> For example, a 2018 study found that each year an athlete played tackle football before age 12 predicted earlier onset of CTE symptoms by an average of two-and-a half-years, but not symptom severity. These CTE symptoms include cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems.<ref name=\"Study finds youth football tied to earlier symptoms of CTE, ESPN, April 30, 2018\">[http://www.espn.com/moresports/story/_/id/23367461/study-finds-youth-football-tied-earlier-cte \"Study finds youth football tied to earlier symptoms of CTE,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623193913/http://www.espn.com/moresports/story/_/id/23367461/study-finds-youth-football-tied-earlier-cte |date=June 23, 2018 }} ESPN, April 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Annals of Neurology, 30 April 2018\">[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ana.25245 Age of First Exposure to Tackle Football and Chronic Traumatic Encephalopathy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215044512/https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ana.25245 |date=December 15, 2018 }}, ''Annals of Neurology'', Michael L. Alosco PhD, Jesse Mez MD, MS, et al., April 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nAfter comparing the script (from the [[Sony Pictures hack]]) with the released movie, ''[[Deadspin]]'' claimed the movie was edited to appease the NFL, including reducing prominence of Roger Goodell and Paul Tagliabue in the film, as well as changing or removing dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/how-sony-changed-concussion-to-make-the-nfl-or-their-l-1749686299|title=How Sony Changed Concussion To Make The NFL (Or Their Lawyers) Happy|first=Timothy|last=Burke|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232559/https://deadspin.com/how-sony-changed-concussion-to-make-the-nfl-or-their-l-1749686299|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/the-nfl-didnt-have-to-screw-will-smiths-concussion-move-1728253804|title=The NFL Didn't Have To Screw Will Smith's Concussion Movie, Hollywood Already Had|first=Kyle|last=Wagner|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232632/https://deadspin.com/the-nfl-didnt-have-to-screw-will-smiths-concussion-move-1728253804|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' discovered emails directly referencing removing \"unflattering moments for the NFL\u201d and removing \u201cmost of the bite\u201d out of the film \u201cfor legal reasons with the NFL\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/02/sports/football/makers-of-sonys-concussion-film-tried-to-avoid-angering-nfl-emails-show.html|title=Sony Altered 'Concussion' Film to Prevent N.F.L. Protests, Emails Show|first=Ken|last=Belson|date=September 1, 2015|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209181117/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/02/sports/football/makers-of-sonys-concussion-film-tried-to-avoid-angering-nfl-emails-show.html|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Landesman stated the changes were made \"to portray the characters and story as accurately as possible to reduce the chance that the league could attack the filmmakers for taking too much creative license\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/heres-an-impossibly-stupid-scene-cut-from-the-concussio-1728360424|title=Here's An Impossibly Stupid Scene That Was Cut From The Concussion Movie|first=Kyle|last=Wagner|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232635/https://deadspin.com/heres-an-impossibly-stupid-scene-cut-from-the-concussio-1728360424|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[League of Denial|League of Denial: The NFL's Concussion Crisis]]''\n* ''[[Head Games (film)|Head Games: The Global Concussion Crisis]]''\n* [[Concussions in American football ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.concussion-movie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|3322364}}\n* {{Mojo title|concussion2015|Concussion}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|concussion_2015|Concussion}}\n\n{{Peter Landesman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Concussion}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:African-American biographical dramas]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films about diseases]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Landesman]]\n[[Category:Sports films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Village Roadshow Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by James Newton Howard]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Landesman]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of players of American football]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of American men]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2015 American sports drama film directed by Peter Landesman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Concussion\n| image          = Concussion poster.jpg\n| alt            = Bennet Omalu in front of some football helmets\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Landesman]]\n| producer       = {{plain list|\n* [[Ridley Scott]]\n* [[Giannina Facio]]\n* David Wolthoff\n* Larry Shuman\n* Elizabeth Cantillon\n}}\n| writer         = Peter Landesman\n| based on       = {{Based on |''Game Brain''|[[Jeanne Marie Laskas]]}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Smith]]\n* [[Alec Baldwin]]\n* [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]]\n* [[Arliss Howard]]\n* [[Paul Reiser]]\n* [[Luke Wilson]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]]}}\n* [[David Morse (actor)|David Morse]]\n* [[Albert Brooks]]\n}}\n| music          = [[James Newton Howard]]\n| cinematography = [[Salvatore Totino]]\n| editing        = [[William Goldenberg]]\n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=deadline-premiere/>\n* [[LStar Capital]]<ref name=deadline-premiere>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/concussion-world-premiere-afi-fest-2015-1201560842/|title='Concussion' To Get World Premiere At AFI Fest|last=Busch|first=Anita|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=February 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927075019/http://deadline.com/2015/09/concussion-world-premiere-afi-fest-2015-1201560842/|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Village Roadshow Pictures]]<ref name=deadline-premiere/>\n* [[Scott Free Productions]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/11/concussion-review-will-smith-scores-touchdown-with-grim-nfl-expose/#57e3598266ce|title='Concussion' Review: Will Smith Scores Touchdown With Timely NFL Muckraker|website=forbes.com|publisher=[[Forbes]]|author=Scott Mendelson|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129043817/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/11/concussion-review-will-smith-scores-touchdown-with-grim-nfl-expose/#57e3598266ce|archive-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|10|[[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]]|2015|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime = 122 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:39--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/concussion-film-0 | title=''CONCUSSION'' (12A) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 2, 2015 | accessdate=November 2, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101144510/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/concussion-film-0 | archive-date=January 1, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $35\u201357 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2015_film_study_v3_WEB.pdf|title=2015 Feature Film Study|last=McDonald|first=Adrian|date=June 15, 2016|publisher=Film L.A.|access-date=June 16, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810062318/https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2015_film_study_v3_WEB.pdf |archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=BOM/>\n| gross = $48.6 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=concussion2015.htm |title=Concussion |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160824213033/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=concussion2015.htm |archive-date=August 24, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Concussion''''' is a 2015 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[Sports film|sports drama]] film directed and written by [[Peter Landesman]], based on the expos\u00e9 \"Game Brain\" by [[Jeanne Marie Laskas]], published in 2009 by ''[[GQ]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bennet Omalu, Concussions, and the NFL: How One Doctor Changed Football Forever|url=https://www.gq.com/story/nfl-players-brain-dementia-study-memory-concussions|work=[[GQ]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|last=Laskas|first=Jeanne Marie|date=September 14, 2009|accessdate=February 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151111053002/http://www.gq.com/story/nfl-players-brain-dementia-study-memory-concussions|archive-date=November 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Set in 2002, the film stars [[Will Smith]] as [[Bennet Omalu|Dr. Bennet Omalu]], a forensic pathologist who fights against the [[National Football League]] trying to suppress his research on [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE) brain degeneration suffered by professional football players. It also stars [[Alec Baldwin]]. \n\nThe film premiered at [[American Film Institute|AFI Fest]] on November 11, 2015 and was released  by [[Columbia Pictures]] on December 25, 2015. The film grossed $48 million worldwide and received mixed reviews, although Smith earned a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] nomination.\n\n==Plot==\n\n[[Steelers]] [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] [[Mike Webster]] is found dead in his [[pickup truck]], after years of [[Self-harm|self-mutilation]] and [[homelessness]]. Before his death, [[Justin Strzelczyk]], a former fellow [[American Football|football]] player, confides in Webster that he is starting to lose his memory, is saying odd things to his children, and nearly threw his wife against the wall. A disoriented Webster brushes Strzelczyk's worries off, and deliriously tells him that the most important thing \"is to finish the game,\" reciting what he said during his [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] speech.\n\n[[Bennet Omalu|Dr. Bennet Omalu]] (Will Smith), a [[Forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]] with the [[Allegheny County, Pennsylvania]] [[coroner]]'s office, handles Webster's [[autopsy]]. He wonders how an otherwise healthy man could have degenerated so quickly, and makes it a point to figure out why he died of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at only fifty years of age. Dr. Omalu closely examines [[Microscope slide|microscope slides]] of Webster's brain and sees evidence of severe [[brain damage|neurotrauma]], concluding that Webster died as a result of the long-term effects of repeated blows to the head, a disorder he terms [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE). With the help of former Steelers [[team doctor]] Dr. Julian Bailes, fellow [[Neurology|neurologist]] [[Steven T. DeKosky|Dr. Steven DeKosky]] and county coroner [[Cyril Wecht|Dr. Cyril Wecht]], Dr. Omalu publishes his findings in [[Neurosurgery_(journal)|''Neurosurgery'']], which are dismissed by the [[National Football League|NFL]].\n\nOver several years, Dr. Omalu discovers that three additional deceased NFL players, [[Justin Strzelczyk]] (2004), [[Terry Long (American football)|Terry Long]] (2005), and [[Andre Waters]] (2006), exhibited symptoms very similar to Webster's. He persuades newly appointed NFL commissioner [[Roger Goodell]] to allow him to present his findings before a player safety committee. However, the NFL does not take him seriously, and he is barred from the committee meeting, forcing the former NFL employee Bailes to give the presentation in place of Dr. Omalu. However, the meeting is a set up, where the NFL claims that the players' head trauma is unrelated to football, but rather, due to past injuries. As he leaves the meeting, former [[National Football League Players Association|NFL Players Association]] executive [[Dave Duerson]] angrily confronts Dr. Omalu and tells him to \"go back to [[Africa]].\"\n\nDr. Omalu is subjected to considerable pressure to back down from his efforts, as football is a widely beloved sport in [[Pittsburgh]], having provided jobs and allowed men to go to college. Wecht is subjected to a politically motivated prosecution on corruption charges, and Dr. Omalu is forced to leave Pittsburgh soon after, lest he be [[deportation|deported]], or sent to prison on petty charges as punishment for tarnishing the NFL's image. Before leaving, he urges the NFL to tell the truth. Dr. Omalu's wife, Prema, suffers a [[miscarriage]] after being followed in her car. The Omalus are forced to leave their dream home outside Pittsburgh, relocating to [[Lodi, California]] where he takes a job with the [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin County]] coroner's office.\n\nThree years later, Dr. Omalu is vindicated when Duerson commits [[suicide]] due to an increasing inability to cope with worsening [[cognitive skill|cognitive function]]. In his [[suicide note]], Duerson acknowledges that Dr. Omalu was right, and offers his brain for future research. Dr. Omalu is invited to address an NFLPA conference on concussions and CTE. He informs them that he once wished he had never known Mike Webster, but by knowing him, he has the responsibility to inform NFL players of the true risks that they take by playing. He says that he holds no resentment for the NFL and tells them to forgive themselves and be at peace. Amid growing scrutiny from [[United States Congress|Congress]], the NFL is forced to take the concussion issue more seriously, and in 2011, [[2011 NFL lockout|NFL players sue the league]] for not properly informing them of the risk of CTE. Dr. Omalu is offered the job of [[Medical examiner|Chief Medical Examiner]] for the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], but the closing credits show Omalu turning the offer down to remain with his family in Lodi, becoming [[Naturalization|naturalized]] as a [[Citizenship of the United States|U.S. citizen]] in February 2015. A final montage includes reports of [[Junior Seau]]'s suicide in 2012 and subsequent [[Concussions in American football#Federal NFL concussion litigation|lawsuits]] brought against the NFL by thousands of former players.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Will Smith]] as Dr. [[Bennet Omalu]]\n* [[Alec Baldwin]] as Dr. Julian Bailes\n* [[Albert Brooks]] as Dr. [[Cyril Wecht]]\n* [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]] as Prema Mutiso\n* [[David Morse]] as [[Mike Webster]]\n** [[Ben McDonnell]] as young [[Mike Webster]]\n* [[Arliss Howard]] as Dr. [[Joseph Maroon]]\n* [[Mike O'Malley]] as Daniel Sullivan\n* [[Eddie Marsan]] as Dr. [[Steven T. DeKosky]]\n* [[Hill Harper]] as Christopher Jones\n* [[Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje]] as [[Dave Duerson]]\n* [[Stephen Moyer]] as Dr. Ron Hamilton\n* [[Richard T. Jones]] as [[Andre Waters]]\n* [[Paul Reiser]] as Dr. Elliot Pellman\n* [[Luke Wilson]] as [[Roger Goodell]]\n* [[Sara Lindsey]] as Gracie\n* [[Matt Willig|Matthew Willig]] as [[Justin Strzelczyk]]\n* [[Bitsie Tulloch]] as Keana Strzelczyk\n* [[Eme Ikwuakor]] as [[Amobi Okoye]]\n* [[Phillip Chorba]] as the technician\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[Ridley Scott]]'s idea of an NFL concussion film was inspired by Dr. Bennett Omalu's study about former NFL stars [[Junior Seau]] and [[Dave Duerson]], both of whom committed suicide after suffering from [[chronic traumatic encephalopathy]] (CTE). Scott was set to direct after his film ''[[Exodus: Gods and Kings]]'', while he and Facio were looking for an A-list writer.<ref name=Concussions>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Ridley Scott To Direct Film About Deadly Effects Of Concussions In Football Players|url=https://deadline.com/2013/11/ridley-scott-to-direct-film-about-deadly-effects-of-concussions-in-football-players-630082/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 7, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912132011/http://deadline.com/2013/11/ridley-scott-to-direct-film-about-deadly-effects-of-concussions-in-football-players-630082/|archive-date=September 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In November and December 2013, two more NFL concussion films were in development, first ''Game Time Decision'' with writer/director and former NFL training camp attendee [[wide receiver]] [[Matthew A. Cherry]] and actor [[Isaiah Washington]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Isaiah Washington, Matthew Cherry Huddle On Football Concussion Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2013/11/isaiah-washington-matthew-cherry-huddle-on-football-concussion-pic-634239/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=November 13, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211120557/http://deadline.com/2013/11/isaiah-washington-matthew-cherry-huddle-on-football-concussion-pic-634239/|archive-date=February 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and another film ''[[League of Denial]]'' with producers [[Walter Parkes]] and [[Laurie MacDonald]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=A Collision Of Football Concussion Projects: Parkes/MacDonald Options NFL Head Injury Expose 'League Of Denial' For Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2013/12/a-collision-of-football-concussion-projects-parkesmacdonald-options-nfl-head-injury-expose-league-of-denial-for-pic-648245/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007021549/http://deadline.com/2013/12/a-collision-of-football-concussion-projects-parkesmacdonald-options-nfl-head-injury-expose-league-of-denial-for-pic-648245/|archive-date=October 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Landesman had based his script on the 2009 [[GQ]] article ''Game Brain'' by [[Jeanne Marie Laskas]].<ref name=Landesman-Sony>{{cite news|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike Jr.|title=Will Smith Eyeing Gridiron Concussion Pic At Sony With Peter Landesman Directing|url=https://deadline.com/2014/06/will-smith-eyeing-gridiron-concussion-pic-739681/|accessdate=October 12, 2014|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=June 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926155201/http://deadline.com/2014/06/will-smith-eyeing-gridiron-concussion-pic-739681/|archive-date=September 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Smith and Marsan previously appeared together in the 2008 [[superhero film]] ''[[Hancock (film)|Hancock]]''. It received $14.4 million in film tax credits from [[Pennsylvania]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] started on October 27, 2014, in [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], and filmed there through mid-January. One of the film's key scenes was shot in Altius Restaurant in the [[Mount Washington (Pittsburgh)|Mt. Washington]] section of Pittsburgh. Other area scenes were shot at a church in Pittsburgh's [[Hill District]], the [[Carnegie Free Library of Braddock|Braddock Carnegie Library]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The Will Smith crew filmed at Braddock Carnegie Library this week|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/12/04/The-Will-Smith-film-continued-production-at-Braddock-Carnegie-Library-this-week/stories/201412040306|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|author=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2018|publisher=PG Publishing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712084116/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/12/04/The-Will-Smith-film-continued-production-at-Braddock-Carnegie-Library-this-week/stories/201412040306|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and in [[downtown Pittsburgh]].<ref name=\"Vancheri\">{{cite web|first=Barbara|last=Vancheri|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/10/31/Will-Smith-movie-shooting-around-town/stories/201410310038|title=Will Smith football movie shooting in Pittsburgh|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=October 31, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2018|publisher=PG Publishing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712083943/http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/movies/2014/10/31/Will-Smith-movie-shooting-around-town/stories/201410310038|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[James Newton Howard]] composed the score for the film. [[Klayton]] (frontman of [[Celldweller]]) provided synth programming for the score.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/celldweller/posts/10153595624591672|author=Klayton|publisher=[[Facebook]]|work=[[Celldweller]] official page |date=August 31, 2015|title=By now, most of you have heard that there's a new Will Smith movie called \"Concussion\" coming out. Some of you probably know that it's being scored by James Newton Howard.|accessdate=August 31, 2015|author-link=Klayton}}</ref> R&B singer [[Leon Bridges]] provided a new song, called \"So Long\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/leon-bridges-so-long-concussion-will-smith-nfl-1201620991/|title='Concussion': Leon Bridges Writes Song for Will Smith Drama|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=October 19, 2015|first=Kristopher|last=Tapley|accessdate=July 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712054549/https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/leon-bridges-so-long-concussion-will-smith-nfl-1201620991/|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe first [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] was released on YouTube on August 31, 2015 by Sony Pictures Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sony Pictures Entertainment|title=Concussion - Official Trailer (2015) - Will Smith|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Io6hPdC41RM|accessdate=August 31, 2015|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=August 31, 2015|author-link=Sony Pictures Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904021542/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Io6hPdC41RM|archive-date=September 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Sony released the film on December 25, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Will Smith's 'Concussion' Drama Set for Christmas Release|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-smiths-concussion-drama-set-for-christmas-release-1201416809/|accessdate=January 28, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=January 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130024013/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/will-smiths-concussion-drama-set-for-christmas-release-1201416809/|archive-date=January 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Marketing included advertisements for the film airing during NFL games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chase|first1=Chris|title=The NFL-shaming 'Concussion' aired a commercial during Thanksgiving game|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/11/concussion-trailer-will-smith-thanksgiving-nfl-game-detroit-philadelphia-allowed-to-air-during-nfl-games|accessdate=December 2, 2015|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129081438/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/11/concussion-trailer-will-smith-thanksgiving-nfl-game-detroit-philadelphia-allowed-to-air-during-nfl-games|archive-date=November 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Concussion'' was released on [[Digital distribution|Digital HD]] on March 15, 2016, before being released two weeks later on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]] and 4K Ultra HD on March 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7690/concussion|title=Concussion (2015)|publisher=DVDs Release Dates|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129115055/http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/7690/concussion|archive-date=January 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Concussion'' grossed $34.5 million in North America and $14.1 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $48.6 million, against a budget of $35 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film opened on December 25, 2015 alongside ''[[Daddy's Home (film)|Daddy's Home]]'', ''[[Joy (film)|Joy]]'', ''[[Point Break (2015 film)|Point Break]]'' and the [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] of ''[[The Big Short (film)|The Big Short]]''. In its opening weekend, the film was projected to gross $8\u201310 million from 2,841 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-box-office-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201670872/|title='Force Awakens' Will Own Christmas Weekend As Five Wide Releases Join The Fray \u2013 Box Office Preview|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 21, 2015|accessdate=December 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223014719/http://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-box-office-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201670872/|archive-date=December 23, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It eventually grossed $10.5 million, finishing 7th at the box office.<ref name=CinemaScore/> Due to Smith's star status and the $35 million production budget, the film was considered a box office disappointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/concussion-adds-to-will-smiths-growing-list-of-recent-box-office-disappointments-whats-going-on-20160111|title='Concussion' adds to Will Smith's recent list of box office disappointments. What's going on?|first=Tambay|last=Obenson|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=January 11, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224082338/http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/concussion-adds-to-will-smiths-growing-list-of-recent-box-office-disappointments-whats-going-on-20160111|archive-date=February 24, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsworldnews.com/articles/55400/20151226/concussion-movie-update-low-box-office-numbers-proves-people-arent-really-concerned-about-cte-video.htm|title=Concussion Movie Update: Low box office numbers prove people aren't really concerned about CTE|first=Eduardo|last=Mendez|work=Sports World News|date=December 26, 2015|accessdate=February 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070618/http://www.sportsworldnews.com/articles/55400/20151226/concussion-movie-update-low-box-office-numbers-proves-people-arent-really-concerned-about-cte-video.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 59% based on 199 reviews, with an average rating of 6.08/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Concussion'' lands a solid, well-acted hit on its impressively timely subject matter, even if its traditional, sports drama structure is a little too safe to deserve a full-on dance in the end zone.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/concussion_2015/ |title=Concussion (2015) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=December 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927121748/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/concussion_2015/ |archive-date=September 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 55 out of 100, based on 39 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/concussion-2015 |title=Concussion Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116092724/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/concussion-2015 |archive-date=January 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> On [[CinemaScore]], audiences gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-weekend-box-office-record-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201672899/ |title='Daddy', 'Joy' & 'Hateful Eight' Reap Fortune As 'Star Wars' Halo Effect Impacts B.O... Can 'Force Awakens' Hit $1 Billion In U.S.? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |first1=Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro |first2=Anita |last2=Busch |date=December 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613000029/https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-weekend-box-office-record-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201672899/ |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWill Smith's performance was praised for being \"sensitive [and] understated\" by ''[[The Denver Post]]''. [[Alec Baldwin]]'s performance was well-received, although his accent was criticized.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_29312021/concussion-movie-review-sensitive-will-smith-anchors-film |title=\"Concussion\" movie review: A sensitive Will Smith anchors film that hits home |date=December 25, 2015 |author=The Associated Press |website=[[The Denver Post]] |publisher=[[Digital First Media]] |accessdate=January 20, 2016 |author-link=The Associated Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127090227/http://www.denverpost.com/movies/ci_29312021/concussion-movie-review-sensitive-will-smith-anchors-film |archive-date=January 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"95%\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Awards\n|-style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[African-American Film Critics Association]]\n| Best Actor\n| [[Will Smith]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Black Reel Awards]]\n| Outstanding Actor, Motion Picture\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Motion Picture\n|''Concussion''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Supporting Actress, Motion Picture\n| [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Ensembles\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[73rd Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Drama]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[The Razzie Redeemer Award]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Film Awards]]\n| Actor of the Year\n| Will Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2016 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Male Performance\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| True Story\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[NAACP Image Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacpimageawards.net/main_winners_nominees.html|title=Nominees|work=47th NACCP Image Awards|publisher=[[NAACP Image Award]]s|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828102253/http://www.naacpimageawards.net/main_winners_nominees.html|archivedate=August 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Motion Picture|Outstanding Motion Picture]]\n|''Concussion''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Actor in a Motion Picture]]\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture]]\n| Gugu Mbatha-Raw\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]]\n| Creative Impact in Acting Award\n| Will Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Directors to Watch\n| [[Peter Landesman]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[20th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| Best Actor\n| Will Smith\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\nFamily members of [[Dave Duerson]], a former NFL player who suffered from CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and committed suicide, claimed the film portrayed Duerson in a bad light. In one scene, Duerson's character called Omalu's character a \"quack\" in addition to telling him \"to go back to Africa\" and \"get away from our game.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = Dave Duerson's Family Says 'Concussion' Film Smears Him|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/sports/football/concussion-movie-smears-dave-duerson-his-family-says.html|newspaper = [[The New York Times]]|publisher = The New York Times Company|date = December 16, 2015|access-date = December 17, 2015|first = Ken|last = Belson|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151217035951/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/sports/football/concussion-movie-smears-dave-duerson-his-family-says.html|archive-date = December 17, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> In another scene, Duerson is shown mocking former NFL player [[Andre Waters]] when he filed an application for benefits in connection with head injuries he sustained while playing in the NFL. Duerson's family members called these scenes false. In response, Landesman, the film's director, stated that the film was \"emotionally and spiritually accurate all the way through\".<ref name=\":0\"/> When asked about the accuracy of the film, Steven DeKosky also noted that it took numerous liberties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/neurology/headtrauma/55657|title='The Great DeKosky' Talks CTE & Concussion|date=January 14, 2016|website=www.medpagetoday.com|access-date=February 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209180046/https://www.medpagetoday.com/neurology/headtrauma/55657|archive-date=February 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n \n''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' science writer Daniel Engber, who has been skeptical of the link between CTE and the deaths of players found to have had it,<ref name=\"Engber Seau article\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2012/05/junior_seau_s_suicide_are_concussions_responsible_.html|last=Engber|first=Daniel|title=The Concussion Panic|newspaper=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|publisher=The Slate Group|date=May 9, 2012|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421101746/http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2012/05/junior_seau_s_suicide_are_concussions_responsible_.html|archive-date=April 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> called the film inaccurate in other ways, for example suggesting that Wecht's arrest on corruption charges was motivated by Omalu's paper, when in fact it was published three months afterwards. \"[The film] feeds into a pervasive myth at the center of the national discussion over football and head injuries,\" he charges.<ref name=\"Engber criticism\">{{cite web|last1=Engber|first1=Daniel|title=Concussion Lies|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2015/12/the_truth_about_will_smith_s_concussion_and_bennet_omalu.html|newspaper=[[Slate (website)|Slate]]|publisher=The Slate Group|accessdate=December 26, 2015|date=December 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225174843/http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2015/12/the_truth_about_will_smith_s_concussion_and_bennet_omalu.html|archive-date=December 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In particular, he cites a 2012 [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] study<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Baron|first1=Sherry L.|last2=Hein|first2=Misty J.|last3=Lehman|first3=Everett|last4=Gersic|first4=Christine M.|title=Body Mass Index, Playing Position, Race, and the Cardiovascular Mortality of Retired Professional Football Players|journal=[[American Journal of Cardiology]]|date=March 15, 2012|volume=109|issue=6|pages=889\u2013896|url=http://www.ajconline.org/article/S0002-9149(11)03387-X/fulltext|accessdate=December 26, 2015|doi=10.1016/j.amjcard.2011.10.050|pmid=22284915|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311113236/http://www.ajconline.org/article/S0002-9149(11)03387-X/fulltext|archive-date=March 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> indicating that football players, on average compared to the population as a whole, live longer and generally healthier lives, though the study also indicates, as Engber concedes, that former football players are also more likely to suffer, and die, from neurodegenerative disease.<ref name=\"Engber criticism\" />\n\nMore recent research and thinking also looks at the steady accumulation of subconcussive blows, in addition to symptomatic concussions, as a major contribution factor in the development of CTE.<ref>[https://www.bu.edu/sph/2018/01/18/hits-not-concussions-cause-cte/ Hits, Not Concussions, Cause CTE] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726005558/https://www.bu.edu/sph/2018/01/18/hits-not-concussions-cause-cte/ |date=July 26, 2018 }}, Boston University School of Public, Jan. 18, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.menshealth.com/health/a21346159/should-kids-play-football/ We Know Football Is Dangerous. So Why Are We Still Letting Our Sons Play It?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725214648/https://www.menshealth.com/health/a21346159/should-kids-play-football/ |date=July 25, 2018 }}, ''Men's Health'', Andrew Lawrence, July 10, 2018.</ref> For example, a 2018 study found that each year an athlete played tackle football before age 12 predicted earlier onset of CTE symptoms by an average of two-and-a half-years, but not symptom severity. These CTE symptoms include cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems.<ref name=\"Study finds youth football tied to earlier symptoms of CTE, ESPN, April 30, 2018\">[http://www.espn.com/moresports/story/_/id/23367461/study-finds-youth-football-tied-earlier-cte \"Study finds youth football tied to earlier symptoms of CTE,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623193913/http://www.espn.com/moresports/story/_/id/23367461/study-finds-youth-football-tied-earlier-cte |date=June 23, 2018 }} ESPN, April 30, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Annals of Neurology, 30 April 2018\">[https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ana.25245 Age of First Exposure to Tackle Football and Chronic Traumatic Encephalopathy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215044512/https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ana.25245 |date=December 15, 2018 }}, ''Annals of Neurology'', Michael L. Alosco PhD, Jesse Mez MD, MS, et al., April 30, 2018.</ref>\n\nAfter comparing the script (from the [[Sony Pictures hack]]) with the released movie, ''[[Deadspin]]'' claimed the movie was edited to appease the NFL, including reducing prominence of Roger Goodell and Paul Tagliabue in the film, as well as changing or removing dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/how-sony-changed-concussion-to-make-the-nfl-or-their-l-1749686299|title=How Sony Changed Concussion To Make The NFL (Or Their Lawyers) Happy|first=Timothy|last=Burke|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232559/https://deadspin.com/how-sony-changed-concussion-to-make-the-nfl-or-their-l-1749686299|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/the-nfl-didnt-have-to-screw-will-smiths-concussion-move-1728253804|title=The NFL Didn't Have To Screw Will Smith's Concussion Movie, Hollywood Already Had|first=Kyle|last=Wagner|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232632/https://deadspin.com/the-nfl-didnt-have-to-screw-will-smiths-concussion-move-1728253804|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' discovered emails directly referencing removing \"unflattering moments for the NFL\u201d and removing \u201cmost of the bite\u201d out of the film \u201cfor legal reasons with the NFL\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/02/sports/football/makers-of-sonys-concussion-film-tried-to-avoid-angering-nfl-emails-show.html|title=Sony Altered 'Concussion' Film to Prevent N.F.L. Protests, Emails Show|first=Ken|last=Belson|date=September 1, 2015|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209181117/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/02/sports/football/makers-of-sonys-concussion-film-tried-to-avoid-angering-nfl-emails-show.html|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Landesman stated the changes were made \"to portray the characters and story as accurately as possible to reduce the chance that the league could attack the filmmakers for taking too much creative license\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/heres-an-impossibly-stupid-scene-cut-from-the-concussio-1728360424|title=Here's An Impossibly Stupid Scene That Was Cut From The Concussion Movie|first=Kyle|last=Wagner|website=Deadspin|access-date=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111232635/https://deadspin.com/heres-an-impossibly-stupid-scene-cut-from-the-concussio-1728360424|archive-date=January 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[League of Denial|League of Denial: The NFL's Concussion Crisis]]''\n* ''[[Head Games (film)|Head Games: The Global Concussion Crisis]]''\n* [[Concussions in American football ]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.concussion-movie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|3322364}}\n* {{Mojo title|concussion2015|Concussion}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|concussion_2015|Concussion}}\n\n{{Peter Landesman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Concussion}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:African-American biographical dramas]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films about diseases]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Landesman]]\n[[Category:Sports films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Village Roadshow Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by James Newton Howard]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Landesman]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of players of American football]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of American men]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concussion_(2015_film)"}
{"title_page": "Pharmakos", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n{{Ancient Greek religion|expanded=practices}}\nA '''pharmak\u00f3s''' ({{lang-el|\u03c6\u03b1\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2}}, plural '''''pharmakoi''''') in [[Ancient Greek religion]] was the ritualistic sacrifice or exile of a human [[scapegoat]] or victim.\n\n==Ritual==\nA slave, a cripple or a criminal was chosen and expelled from the community at times of disaster (famine, invasion or plague) or at times of calendrical crisis. It was believed that this would bring about purification. On the first day of the [[Thargelia]], a festival of [[Apollo]] at Athens, two men, the ''Pharmakoi'', were led out as if to be sacrificed as an expiation.\n\nSome scholia state that ''pharmakoi'' were actually sacrificed (thrown from a cliff or burned), but many modern scholars reject this, arguing that the earliest source for the ''pharmakos'' (the iambic satirist [[Hipponax]]) shows the ''pharmakoi'' being beaten and stoned, but not executed. A more plausible explanation would be that sometimes they were executed and sometimes not, depending on the attitude of the victim. For instance, a deliberate unrepentant murderer would most likely be put to death.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nIn ''Aesop in Delphi'' (1961), Anton Wiechers discussed the parallels between the legendary biography of [[Aesop]] (in which he is unjustly tried and executed by the Delphians) and the ''pharmakos'' ritual. For example, Aesop is grotesquely deformed, as was the ''pharmakos'' in some traditions; and Aesop was thrown from a cliff, as was the pharmakos in some traditions.\n\nGregory Nagy, in ''Best of the Achaeans'' (1979), compared Aesop's ''pharmakos'' death to the \"worst\" of the Achaeans in the ''[[Iliad]]'', Thersites. More recently, both Daniel Ogden, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' (1997) and [[Todd Compton]], ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero'' (2006) examine poet ''pharmakoi''. Compton surveys important poets who were exiled, executed or suffered unjust trials, either in history, legend or Greek or [[Indo-European myth]].\n\n==Modern interpretations<!--'Plato's Pharmacy' redirects here-->==\n[[Walter Burkert]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Girard]] have written influential modern interpretations of the ''pharmakos'' rite. Burkert shows that humans were sacrificed or expelled after being fed well, and, according to some sources, their ashes were scattered to the ocean. This was a purification ritual, a form of societal [[catharsis]].<ref>Walter Burkert. ''Greek Religion'', p. 82.</ref> Girard likewise discusses the connection between catharsis, sacrifice, and purification.<ref>Ren\u00e9 Girard. ''I See Satan Fall Like Lightning'', pp. 37\u201338, 51, 78, 131</ref> Some scholars have connected the practice of [[ostracism]], in which a prominent politician was exiled from Athens after a vote using pottery pieces, with the ''pharmakos'' custom. However, the ostracism exile was only for a fixed time, as opposed to the finality of the ''pharmakos'' execution or expulsion.\n\nPharmakos is also used as a vital term in Derridean [[deconstruction]]. In his essay \"'''Plato's Pharmacy'''\"<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->,<ref>''Dissemination'', translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981</ref> [[Derrida]] deconstructs several texts by [[Plato]], such as ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'', and reveals the inter-connection between the word chain ''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus'' and the notably absent word ''pharmakos''. In doing so, he attacks the boundary between inside and outside, declaring that the outside (pharmakos, never uttered by Plato) is always-already present right behind the inside (''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus''). As a concept, Pharmakos can be said to be related to other Derridian terms such as \"[[Trace (deconstruction)|Trace]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pharmacy#Etymology|Etymology of ''pharmacy'']]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rug.nl/Bibliotheek/catalogiBestanden/elekPubRUG/keur/11Bremmer Bremmer, Jan N.], [http://keur.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/wetenschappers/11/6576/ \"Scapegoat Rituals in Ancient Greece\"], ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', Vol. 87. (1983), pp.&nbsp;299\u2013320.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Greek Religion'', Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1985.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Structure and History in Greek Mythology''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1979, 59-77.\n*Calcagnetti, Daniel J., \"Neuropharmacology: From Cellular Receptors and Neurotransmitter Synthesis to Neuropathology & Drug Addiction\", First Edition, 2006.\n*[[Todd Compton|Compton, Todd]], [http://toddmcompton.com/pharmakos.htm \u201cThe Pharmakos Ritual: Testimonia.\u201d]\n*Compton, Todd, ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero in Greco-Roman and Indo-European Myth and History''. Washington, D.C.: Center for Hellenic Studies/Harvard University Press, 2006.\n*Derrida, Jacques, \"Dissemination\", translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981.\n*Fiore, Robert L., [https://www.jstor.org/stable/473965 \"Alarcon's El dueno de las estrellas: Hero and Pharmakos\"], ''Hispanic Review'', Vol. 61, No. 2, Earle Homage Issue (Spring, 1993), pp.&nbsp;185\u2013199.\n*Frazer, James. ''The Golden Bough. Part VI. The Scapegoat'', pp.&nbsp;252ff.\n*Girard, Ren\u00e9. ''The Scapegoat.'' Trans. Y. Freccero. Baltimore, 1986.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Epilegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Prolegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1908.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Themis: a Study of the Social Origin of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Hirayama, Koji, [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/49_2001.html#hirayama ''Stoning in the Pharmakos Ritual''], [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/jcs.html Journal of Classical Studies], XLIX(2001), Classical Society of Japan, [[Kyoto University]].\n*Hughes, Dennis, ''Human Sacrifice in Ancient Greece'', London 1991, pp.&nbsp;139\u2013165.\n*Nagy, Gregory. [http://www.press.jhu.edu/books/nagy/BofA.html ''The Best of the Achaeans: Concepts of the Hero in Archaic Greek Poetry.''] The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1979, pp.&nbsp;280\u201390 in print edition.\n*Nilsson, Martin P., [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/gpr/index.htm ''Greek Popular Religion''], 1940. See the discussion of the Thargelia in the chapter \u201cRural Customs and Festivals.\u201d\n*Ogden, Daniel, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' London 1997, pp.&nbsp;15\u201346.\n*Parker, Robert, ''Miasma, Pollution and Purification in Early Greek Religion.'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1983, pp.&nbsp;24\u201326, 257-280.\n*Rinella, Michael A., ''Pharmakon:  Plato, Drug Culture, and Identity in Ancient Athens''. Lanham, MD:  Lexington Books, 2010, 73-74.\n* Whibley, Leonard, MA, ''A Companion to Greek Studies''. Cambridge University Press.\n*Wiechers, A. ''Aesop in Delphi''. Meisenheim am Glan 1961.\n\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n{{Ancient Greek religion|expanded=practices}}\nA '''pharmak\u00f3s''' ({{lang-el|\u03c6\u03b1\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2}}, plural '''''pharmakoi''''') in [[Ancient Greek religion]] was the ritualistic sacrifice or exile of a human [[scapegoat]] or victim.\n\n==Ritual==\nA slave, a cripple or a criminal was chosen and expelled from the community at times of disaster (famine, invasion or plague) or at times of calendrical crisis. It was believed that this would bring about purification. On the first day of the [[Thargelia]], a festival of [[Apollo]] at Athens, two men, the ''Pharmakoi'', were led out as if to be sacrificed as an expiation.\n\nSome scholia state that ''pharmakoi'' were actually sacrificed (thrown from a cliff or burned), but many modern scholars reject this, arguing that the earliest source for the ''pharmakos'' (the iambic satirist [[Hipponax]]) shows the ''pharmakoi'' being beaten and stoned, but not executed. A more plausible explanation would be that sometimes they were executed and sometimes not, depending on the attitude of the victim. For instance, a deliberate unrepentant murderer would most likely be put to death.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nIn ''Aesop in Delphi'' (1961), Anton Wiechers discussed the parallels between the legendary biography of [[Aesop]] (in which he is unjustly tried and executed by the Delphians) and the ''pharmakos'' ritual. For example, Aesop is grotesquely deformed, as was the ''pharmakos'' in some traditions; and Aesop was thrown from a cliff, as was the pharmakos in some traditions.\n\nGregory Nagy, in ''Best of the Achaeans'' (1979), compared Aesop's ''pharmakos'' death to the \"worst\" of the Achaeans in the ''[[Iliad]]'', Thersites. More recently, both Daniel Ogden, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' (1997) and [[Todd Compton]], ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero'' (2006) examine poet ''pharmakoi''. Compton surveys important poets who were exiled, executed or suffered unjust trials, either in history, legend or Greek or [[Indo-European myth]].\n\n==Modern interpretations<!--'Plato's Pharmacy' redirects here-->==\n[[Walter Burkert]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Girard]] have written influential modern interpretations of the ''pharmakos'' rite. Burkert shows that humans were sacrificed or expelled after being fed well, and, according to some sources, their ashes were scattered to the ocean. This was a purification ritual, a form of societal [[catharsis]].<ref>Walter Burkert. ''Greek Religion'', p. 82.</ref> Girard likewise discusses the connection between catharsis, sacrifice, and purification.<ref>Ren\u00e9 Girard. ''I See Satan Fall Like Lightning'', pp. 37\u201338, 51, 78, 131</ref> Some scholars have connected the practice of [[ostracism]], in which a prominent politician was exiled from Athens after a vote using pottery pieces, with the ''pharmakos'' custom. However, the ostracism exile was only for a fixed time, as opposed to the finality of the ''pharmakos'' execution or expulsion.\n\nPharmakos is also used as a vital term in Derridean [[deconstruction]]. In his essay \"'''Plato's Pharmacy'''\"<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->,<ref>''Dissemination'', translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981</ref> [[Derrida]] deconstructs several texts by [[Plato]], such as ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'', and reveals the inter-connection between the word chain ''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus'' and the notably absent word ''pharmakos''. In doing so, he attacks the boundary between inside and outside, declaring that the outside (pharmakos, never uttered by Plato) is always-already present right behind the inside (''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus''). As a concept, Pharmakos can be said to be related to other Derridian terms such as \"[[Trace (philosophy)|trace]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pharmacy#Etymology|Etymology of ''pharmacy'']]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rug.nl/Bibliotheek/catalogiBestanden/elekPubRUG/keur/11Bremmer Bremmer, Jan N.], [http://keur.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/wetenschappers/11/6576/ \"Scapegoat Rituals in Ancient Greece\"], ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', Vol. 87. (1983), pp.&nbsp;299\u2013320.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Greek Religion'', Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1985.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Structure and History in Greek Mythology''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1979, 59-77.\n*Calcagnetti, Daniel J., \"Neuropharmacology: From Cellular Receptors and Neurotransmitter Synthesis to Neuropathology & Drug Addiction\", First Edition, 2006.\n*[[Todd Compton|Compton, Todd]], [http://toddmcompton.com/pharmakos.htm \u201cThe Pharmakos Ritual: Testimonia.\u201d]\n*Compton, Todd, ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero in Greco-Roman and Indo-European Myth and History''. Washington, D.C.: Center for Hellenic Studies/Harvard University Press, 2006.\n*Derrida, Jacques, \"Dissemination\", translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981.\n*Fiore, Robert L., [https://www.jstor.org/stable/473965 \"Alarcon's El dueno de las estrellas: Hero and Pharmakos\"], ''Hispanic Review'', Vol. 61, No. 2, Earle Homage Issue (Spring, 1993), pp.&nbsp;185\u2013199.\n*Frazer, James. ''The Golden Bough. Part VI. The Scapegoat'', pp.&nbsp;252ff.\n*Girard, Ren\u00e9. ''The Scapegoat.'' Trans. Y. Freccero. Baltimore, 1986.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Epilegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Prolegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1908.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Themis: a Study of the Social Origin of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Hirayama, Koji, [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/49_2001.html#hirayama ''Stoning in the Pharmakos Ritual''], [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/jcs.html Journal of Classical Studies], XLIX(2001), Classical Society of Japan, [[Kyoto University]].\n*Hughes, Dennis, ''Human Sacrifice in Ancient Greece'', London 1991, pp.&nbsp;139\u2013165.\n*Nagy, Gregory. [http://www.press.jhu.edu/books/nagy/BofA.html ''The Best of the Achaeans: Concepts of the Hero in Archaic Greek Poetry.''] The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1979, pp.&nbsp;280\u201390 in print edition.\n*Nilsson, Martin P., [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/gpr/index.htm ''Greek Popular Religion''], 1940. See the discussion of the Thargelia in the chapter \u201cRural Customs and Festivals.\u201d\n*Ogden, Daniel, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' London 1997, pp.&nbsp;15\u201346.\n*Parker, Robert, ''Miasma, Pollution and Purification in Early Greek Religion.'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1983, pp.&nbsp;24\u201326, 257-280.\n*Rinella, Michael A., ''Pharmakon:  Plato, Drug Culture, and Identity in Ancient Athens''. Lanham, MD:  Lexington Books, 2010, 73-74.\n* 